/**
29 
 * <p>Operations on {@link java.lang.String} that are
30 
 * {@code null} safe.</p>
31 
 *
32 
 * <ul>
33 
 *  <li><b>IsEmpty/IsBlank</b>
34 
 *      - checks if a String contains text</li>
35 
 *  <li><b>Trim/Strip</b>
36 
 *      - removes leading and trailing whitespace</li>
37 
 *  <li><b>Equals</b>
38 
 *      - compares two strings null-safe</li>
39 
 *  <li><b>startsWith</b>
40 
 *      - check if a String starts with a prefix null-safe</li>
41 
 *  <li><b>endsWith</b>
42 
 *      - check if a String ends with a suffix null-safe</li>
43 
 *  <li><b>IndexOf/LastIndexOf/Contains</b>
44 
 *      - null-safe index-of checks
45 
 *  <li><b>IndexOfAny/LastIndexOfAny/IndexOfAnyBut/LastIndexOfAnyBut</b>
46 
 *      - index-of any of a set of Strings</li>
47 
 *  <li><b>ContainsOnly/ContainsNone/ContainsAny</b>
48 
 *      - does String contains only/none/any of these characters</li>
49 
 *  <li><b>Substring/Left/Right/Mid</b>
50 
 *      - null-safe substring extractions</li>
51 
 *  <li><b>SubstringBefore/SubstringAfter/SubstringBetween</b>
52 
 *      - substring extraction relative to other strings</li>
53 
 *  <li><b>Split/Join</b>
54 
 *      - splits a String into an array of substrings and vice versa</li>
55 
 *  <li><b>Remove/Delete</b>
56 
 *      - removes part of a String</li>
57 
 *  <li><b>Replace/Overlay</b>
58 
 *      - Searches a String and replaces one String with another</li>
59 
 *  <li><b>Chomp/Chop</b>
60 
 *      - removes the last part of a String</li>
61 
 *  <li><b>AppendIfMissing</b>
62 
 *      - appends a suffix to the end of the String if not present</li>
63 
 *  <li><b>PrependIfMissing</b>
64 
 *      - prepends a prefix to the start of the String if not present</li>
65 
 *  <li><b>LeftPad/RightPad/Center/Repeat</b>
66 
 *      - pads a String</li>
67 
 *  <li><b>UpperCase/LowerCase/SwapCase/Capitalize/Uncapitalize</b>
68 
 *      - changes the case of a String</li>
69 
 *  <li><b>CountMatches</b>
70 
 *      - counts the number of occurrences of one String in another</li>
71 
 *  <li><b>IsAlpha/IsNumeric/IsWhitespace/IsAsciiPrintable</b>
72 
 *      - checks the characters in a String</li>
73 
 *  <li><b>DefaultString</b>
74 
 *      - protects against a null input String</li>
75 
 *  <li><b>Reverse/ReverseDelimited</b>
76 
 *      - reverses a String</li>
77 
 *  <li><b>Abbreviate</b>
78 
 *      - abbreviates a string using ellipsis</li>
79 
 *  <li><b>Difference</b>
80 
 *      - compares Strings and reports on their differences</li>
81 
 *  <li><b>LevenshteinDistance</b>
82 
 *      - the number of changes needed to change one String into another</li>
83 
 * </ul>
84 
 *
85 
 * <p>The {@code StringUtils} class defines certain words related to
86 
 * String handling.</p>
87 
 *
88 
 * <ul>
89 
 *  <li>null - {@code null}</li>
90 
 *  <li>empty - a zero-length string ({@code ""})</li>
91 
 *  <li>space - the space character ({@code ' '}, char 32)</li>
92 
 *  <li>whitespace - the characters defined by {@link Character#isWhitespace(char)}</li>
93 
 *  <li>trim - the characters &lt;= 32 as in {@link String#trim()}</li>
94 
 * </ul>
95 
 *
96 
 * <p>{@code StringUtils} handles {@code null} input Strings quietly.
97 
 * That is to say that a {@code null} input will return {@code null}.
98 
 * Where a {@code boolean} or {@code int} is being returned
99 
 * details vary by method.</p>
100 
 *
101 
 * <p>A side effect of the {@code null} handling is that a
102 
 * {@code NullPointerException} should be considered a bug in
103 
 * {@code StringUtils}.</p>
104 
 *
105 
 * <p>Methods in this class give sample code to explain their operation.
106 
 * The symbol {@code *} is used to indicate any input including {@code null}.</p>
107 
 *
108 
 * <p>#ThreadSafe#</p>
109 
 * @see java.lang.String
110 
 * @since 1.0
111 
 * @version $Id$
112 
 */
113 
//@Immutable
114 
public class StringUtils {
115 
    // Performance testing notes (JDK 1.4, Jul03, scolebourne)
116 
    // Whitespace:
117 
    // Character.isWhitespace() is faster than WHITESPACE.indexOf()
118 
    // where WHITESPACE is a string of all whitespace characters
119 
    //
120 
    // Character access:
121 
    // String.charAt(n) versus toCharArray(), then array[n]
122 
    // String.charAt(n) is about 15% worse for a 10K string
123 
    // They are about equal for a length 50 string
124 
    // String.charAt(n) is about 4 times better for a length 3 string
125 
    // String.charAt(n) is best bet overall
126 
    //
127 
    // Append:
128 
    // String.concat about twice as fast as StringBuffer.append
129 
    // (not sure who tested this)
130
131

    /**
174 
     * A regex pattern for recognizing blocks of whitespace characters.
175 
     * The apparent convolutedness of the pattern serves the purpose of
176 
     * ignoring "blocks" consisting of only a single space:  the pattern
177 
     * is used only to normalize whitespace, condensing "blocks" down to a
178 
     * single space, thus matching the same would likely cause a great
179 
     * many noop replacements.
180 
     */
181 
    private static final Pattern WHITESPACE_PATTERN = Pattern.compile("(?: \\s|[\\s&&[^ ]])\\s*");
182
183 
    /**
184 
     * <p>{@code StringUtils} instances should NOT be constructed in
185 
     * standard programming. Instead, the class should be used as
186 
     * {@code StringUtils.trim(" foo ");}.</p>
187 
     *
188 
     * <p>This constructor is public to permit tools that require a JavaBean
189 
     * instance to operate.</p>
190 
     */
191 
    public StringUtils() {
192 
        super();
193 
    }

    /**
456 
     * <p>Strips any of a set of characters from the start and end of a String.
457 
     * This is similar to {@link String#trim()} but allows the characters
458 
     * to be stripped to be controlled.</p>
459 
     *
460 
     * <p>A {@code null} input String returns {@code null}.
461 
     * An empty string ("") input returns the empty string.</p>

     *
463 
     * <p>If the stripChars String is {@code null}, whitespace is
464 
     * stripped as defined by {@link Character#isWhitespace(char)}.
465 
     * Alternatively use {@link #strip(String)}.</p>

     *
467 
     * <pre>

     * StringUtils.strip(null, *)          = null

     * StringUtils.strip("", *)            = ""
470 
     * StringUtils.strip("abc", null)      = "abc"
471 
     * StringUtils.strip("  abc", null)    = "abc"
472 
     * StringUtils.strip("abc  ", null)    = "abc"
473 
     * StringUtils.strip(" abc ", null)    = "abc"
474 
     * StringUtils.strip("  abcyx", "xyz") = "  abc"
475 
     * </pre>
476 
     *
477 
     * @param str  the String to remove characters from, may be null
478

480 
     */

6752 
        This implementation only computes the distance if it's less than or equal to the
6753 
        threshold value, returning -1 if it's greater.  The advantage is performance: unbounded
6754 
        distance is O(nm), but a bound of k allows us to reduce it to O(km) time by only
6755 
        computing a diagonal stripe of width 2k + 1 of the cost table.
6756 
        It is also possible to use this to compute the unbounded Levenshtein distance by starting
6757 
        the threshold at 1 and doubling each time until the distance is found; this is O(dm), where
6758 
        d is the distance.
6759

6761

6765

6768

6769

    /**
7059 
     * <p>
7060 
     * Similar to <a
7061 
     * href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize-space">http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize
7062 
     * -space</a>
7063 
     * </p>
7064 
     * <p>
7065 
     * The function returns the argument string with whitespace normalized by using
7066 
     * <code>{@link #trim(String)}</code> to remove leading and trailing whitespace
7067 
     * and then replacing sequences of whitespace characters by a single space.
7068 
     * </p>
7069 
     * In XML Whitespace characters are the same as those allowed by the <a
7070 
     * href="http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-xml/#NT-S">S</a> production, which is S ::= (#x20 | #x9 | #xD | #xA)+
7071 
     * <p>
7072 
     * Java's regexp pattern \s defines whitespace as [ \t\n\x0B\f\r]
7073 
     * <p>
7074 
     * For reference:
7075 
     * <ul>
7076 
     * <li>\x0B = vertical tab</li>
7077 
     * <li>\f = #xC = form feed</li>
7078 
     * <li>#x20 = space</li>
7079 
     * <li>#x9 = \t</li>
7080 
     * <li>#xA = \n</li>
7081 
     * <li>#xD = \r</li>
7082 
     * </ul>
7083 
     * </p>
7084 
     * <p>
7085 
     * The difference is that Java's whitespace includes vertical tab and form feed, which this functional will also
7086 
     * normalize. Additionally <code>{@link #trim(String)}</code> removes control characters (char &lt;= 32) from both
7087 
     * ends of this String.
7088 
     * </p>
7089 
     *
7090 
     * @see Pattern
7091 
     * @see #trim(String)
7092 
     * @see <a
7093 
     *      href="http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize-space">http://www.w3.org/TR/xpath/#function-normalize-space</a>
7094 
     * @param str the source String to normalize whitespaces from, may be null
7095 
     * @return the modified string with whitespace normalized, {@code null} if null String input
7096 
     *
7097 
     * @since 3.0
7098 
     */
7099
